From: Cline (audit B3) <audit@ask>
Date: Tue, 05 May 2026 11:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] auto_bridge: bound L2FLOWA_IP_SRC/DST nla_len before memcpy

Audit finding auto_bridge AB-01 (plans/audit/AUDIT-auto_bridge.md).

abm_nl_rcv_msg() at L2FLOW_MSG_ENTRY does:

    memcpy(&l2flow_temp.l3.saddr.all, nla_data(tb[L2FLOWA_IP_SRC]),
           nla_len(tb[L2FLOWA_IP_SRC]));

`l3.saddr.all` is a fixed 16-byte buffer (`u32 all[4]`, see
auto_bridge_private.h). nla_len() returns the attribute payload length
from the netlink message — attacker-controlled, validated only against
overall netlink message length, so up to ~64 KB.

Without a bound, an attacker (post-B2/AB-02 capability check is
required, but a privileged misbehaving userspace component or a
compromised CAP_NET_ADMIN process) can supply L2FLOWA_IP_SRC with a
40-byte payload and get a 24-byte stack OOB write. 64 KB payload would
do far more damage. nla_get_in6_addr() is the canonical way to copy a
v6 address out of a netlink attribute, but the existing code path uses
the raw memcpy because it accepts both v4 (4 bytes) and v6 (16 bytes)
into the union.

This patch adds a length sanity check before each memcpy. Valid
payloads are EXACTLY 4 (IPv4) or 16 (IPv6) bytes. Anything else is
silently rejected as -EINVAL and the rest of the L2FLOW entry is
discarded, matching the existing -EAGAIN drop pattern at L509.

Audit reference: plans/audit/AUDIT-auto_bridge.md AB-01
Signed-off-by: Cline <audit@ask>
---
diff --git a/auto_bridge/auto_bridge.c b/auto_bridge/auto_bridge.c
--- a/auto_bridge/auto_bridge.c
+++ b/auto_bridge/auto_bridge.c
@@ -537,11 +537,33 @@ static int abm_nl_rcv_msg(struct sk_buff *skb, struct nlmsghdr *nlh ,struct netl
 if(tb[L2FLOWA_PPP_S_ID])
 l2flow_temp.session_id = nla_get_u16(tb[L2FLOWA_PPP_S_ID]);
 
-if(tb[L2FLOWA_IP_SRC])
-memcpy(&l2flow_temp.l3.saddr.all, nla_data(tb[L2FLOWA_IP_SRC]), nla_len(tb[L2FLOWA_IP_SRC]));
-
-if(tb[L2FLOWA_IP_DST])
-memcpy(&l2flow_temp.l3.daddr.all, nla_data(tb[L2FLOWA_IP_DST]), nla_len(tb[L2FLOWA_IP_DST]));
+/* B3/AB-01: l3.{saddr,daddr}.all is a fixed 16-byte (u32[4]) buffer.
+ * nla_len() is attacker-controlled (validated only against overall
+ * netlink message length, up to ~64 KB), so the memcpy must be
+ * length-checked. Valid IP attribute payloads are EXACTLY 4 bytes
+ * (IPv4) or 16 bytes (IPv6). Anything else is rejected as -EINVAL
+ * and the entry is dropped, matching the existing -EAGAIN drop
+ * pattern earlier in this handler. */
+if(tb[L2FLOWA_IP_SRC]) {
+int alen = nla_len(tb[L2FLOWA_IP_SRC]);
+if (alen != 4 && alen != 16) {
+err = -EINVAL;
+goto out;
+}
+memcpy(&l2flow_temp.l3.saddr.all, nla_data(tb[L2FLOWA_IP_SRC]), alen);
+}
+
+if(tb[L2FLOWA_IP_DST]) {
+int alen = nla_len(tb[L2FLOWA_IP_DST]);
+if (alen != 4 && alen != 16) {
+err = -EINVAL;
+goto out;
+}
+memcpy(&l2flow_temp.l3.daddr.all, nla_data(tb[L2FLOWA_IP_DST]), alen);
+}
 
 if(tb[L2FLOWA_IP_PROTO])
 l2flow_temp.l3.proto= nla_get_u8(tb[L2FLOWA_IP_PROTO]);